{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:08:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:08:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14030"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14030"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.18,0.61,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105825"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6679"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14030"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1894"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17315"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39977"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of anuria. He has a medical history of benign prostatic hyperplasia and hypertension. His regular medications are tamsulosin and amlodipine. On examination, he appears unwell with a distended, tender lower abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 104/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) is 15 and no additional sounds are audible on cardiovascular examination. A bladder scan reveals 1200 mL of urine. After catheterisation, he produces 3 L of urine over the next four hours. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum sodium: 142 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 320 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urea: 28 mmol/L (2.5-6.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important aspect of acute management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent haemodialysis","Administration of furosemide and electrolyte monitoring","Urgent urological intervention","Administration of fluids and electrolyte monitoring","Commencement of dutasteride."],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute urinary retention, likely due to his benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) with resultant acute kidney injury (AKI). After catheterisation, he develops post-obstructive diuresis, evidenced by the large urine output of 3 L in 4 hours. The most critical aspect of ongoing management in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003Eadministration of fluids and electrolyte monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-obstructive diuresis can lead to significant fluid and electrolyte imbalances. The massive urine output can quickly result in hypovolemia and electrolyte derangements, particularly hypokalaemia. These imbalances can lead to serious complications if not properly managed. Regular monitoring allows for timely intervention and appropriate replacement of losses. Often in the early stages of post-obstructive diuresis, intravenous crystalloid fluids need to be administered at a replacement rate of 50-75% of urinary losses/hour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. While the patient has elevated creatinine and urea levels, these are expected to improve with relief of the urinary obstruction. The hyperkalaemia is only mild, and there are no signs of severe uraemia (GCS is 15, and cardiovascular examination is normal).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this situation. The patient is already producing large volumes of urine, and a diuretic would exacerbate fluid losses and potentially worsen electrolyte imbalances and hypovolaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent urological intervention\u003C/strong\u003E will likely be necessary to address the underlying cause of urinary retention (BPH in this case). However, managing the acute consequences of post-obstructive diuresis takes precedence in the immediate term.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencement of dutasteride \u003C/strong\u003Emay be considered for long-term management of BPH, but it is not the most important aspect of acute management. Dutasteride is a 5-alpha reductase inhibitor that reduces prostate size over time, but it would not address the immediate concerns of fluid and electrolyte imbalances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, close monitoring of fluid balance and electrolytes is essential in the acute management of post-obstructive diuresis. This allows for appropriate fluid and electrolyte replacement, preventing complications such as hypovolemia, electrolyte imbalances, and acute kidney injury. The management should be tailored to the individual patient based on regular assessments of their clinical status, urine output, and laboratory values.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-obstructive diuresis can lead to significant fluid and electrolyte imbalances, particularly hypovolemia and hypokalaemia.","Close monitoring of fluid balance and electrolytes is crucial in managing patients with post-obstructive diuresis to prevent complications.","Replacement of fluid and electrolyte losses should be tailored to individual patient needs based on regular assessments."],"references":["Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Sharma S. Postobstructive Diuresis [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459387/","Dutasteride (Avodart) and dutasteride with tamsulosin (Duodart) for lower urinary tract symptoms due to benign prostatic hyperplasia [Internet]. NPS MedicineWise. 2011. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/radar/articles/dutasteride-avodart-and-dutasteride-with-tamsulosin-duodart-for-lower-urinary-tract-symptoms-due-to-benign-prostatic-hyperplasia"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14030"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:54:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-28T16:48:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6679"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105825"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T0